  "method": "We propose HyperZero-PEFT, a forward-only, hypernetwork-driven adapter scheme that adapts a frozen LLM using a tiny number of additional parameters while matching full fine-tuning. Insert lightweight, parallel adapters in the FFN (LoRA-style down/up projections) and short learned key/value prefixes in attention. A single shared hypernetwork generates all adapter and prefix weights for every layer from compact inputs that concatenate a task embedding, a layer-id embedding, and a block-type embedding. The generated modules are injected with residual scaling and per-layer learned gates to softly select where adaptation matters most. Only the hypernetwork, small embedding tables, the per-layer gates, and optionally layer norms are trained; the LLM weights remain frozen.\n\nTraining is performed with a two-point zeroth-order (ZO) estimator on the hypernetwork parameters, eliminating backpropagation through the base LLM so memory stays near inference. At each step, draw an antithetic perturbation for the hypernetwork weights, run two forward passes to compute a finite-difference loss, and update with an Adam-like optimizer. We deterministically resample perturbations by seed to reduce variance and enable gradient accumulation without extra memory. Because the hypernetwork is small and the base model is frozen, a single consumer GPU (e.g., 8–24 GB) can train billions-parameter LLMs with near-inference memory and throughput.\n\nTo maximize accuracy under a tiny parameter budget, we add a short sensitivity warm-up that allocates rank and prefix length where they help most. Using a small held-out set, we probe each layer by perturbing its hyper-embedding and measuring loss change, then allocate higher LoRA rank and/or longer prefixes to the top-k most sensitive layers while shrinking others to minimal or zero rank. The hypernetwork learns to specialize by layer and block type, amortizing parameters across the whole stack and across tasks via the task embedding.\n\nAt inference, the hypernetwork generates per-layer adapter/prefix weights on the fly or caches them after the first use; switching tasks reduces to swapping a task embedding. The method is compatible with quantized bases (e.g., 4/8-bit) since only small-side modules are trained and applied in higher precision. With typical settings (LoRA rank 4–16; prefix length 8–16; hypernetwork at 0.2%–0.6% of base), HyperZero-PEFT achieves performance on par with full fine-tuning while training and storing orders of magnitude fewer parameters.",
  "rationale": "HyperZero-PEFT combines two complementary ideas: (a) a shared hypernetwork that amortizes the cost of generating effective adapters and attention prefixes across all layers and tasks, and (b) forward-only zeroth-order training so adaptation fits on consumer hardware. Prior work shows that hypernetworks conditioned on task/layer/block embeddings can produce both adapter and prefix weights that rival or beat standard PEFT while training a tiny fraction of parameters, suggesting strong capacity-per-parameter. ZO optimization, in turn, matches the memory footprint of inference by avoiding backpropagation, and has been shown to scale to large LLMs on a single 24 GB GPU with competitive convergence.\n\nThe sensitivity-based budget allocator exploits the observed low effective curvature rank in LLMs to place rank and prefix length where they matter, letting a very small parameter budget approximate the function class of full fine-tuning. Together, these components deliver near-FT accuracy while training and storing only a small, task-portable hypernetwork and embeddings—precisely the constraints required for consumer devices.",
