  "method": "We propose Sparse Global–Local Adapters (SGLA), a parameter‑efficient adaptation scheme that adds fewer than ~0.5–1.0% new parameters to a frozen pretrained LLM while approaching full fine‑tuning performance. SGLA combines two complementary components: (1) cross‑layer global conditioning via lightweight learned prefixes that inject a task/domain embedding into the attention stacks of selected layers, and (2) a tiny bank of low‑rank adapters per selected layer with prototype‑routed gating so the model can express task‑specific transformations without touching the base weights.\n\nLayer placement is selected automatically with a probe‑and‑prune procedure. First, we run the frozen LLM and attach layer‑wise linear probes to measure which layers most correlate with downstream task signal on a small validation set. We then initialize small scalar gates per candidate layer and train under a group‑sparsity regularizer so only the few most useful layers remain active. We place SGLA modules only in these layers (typically 4–8 late layers on decoder models), sharply reducing the parameter budget while targeting the layers where task knowledge concentrates.\n\nWithin each selected layer, we (a) prepend a short, learned key/value prefix (e.g., 8–32 virtual tokens) that acts as a global task attribute, injected into the attention computation across the forward pass; and (b) attach a tiny bank (e.g., 2–4) of low‑rank adapters to the attention and MLP projections with very small ranks (r≈4–8). A lightweight routing head matches the current hidden state to a handful of learned prototypes (cosine similarity), producing mixture weights that softly select which adapter(s) to engage for the token or sequence. This yields mixture‑of‑adapters expressivity with minimal added parameters and compute. The routing head also outputs a calibrated confidence signal that we use to schedule updates.\n\nTraining proceeds in two short phases on consumer hardware. Phase A (stabilize and align): we distill token‑level logits from a reference model (e.g., a fully fine‑tuned or larger teacher when available) and adversarially align intermediate representations between the adapted and frozen bases to preserve general capability. The prefix vectors are updated with a conservative, uncertainty‑guided EMA: examples the router deems uncertain get larger prompt updates, while certain ones get smaller nudges. Phase B (task specialization): we optimize the task objective (e.g., SFT or preference learning) only over the SGLA parameters. We use a loss‑adaptive momentum optimizer that estimates noise online from the scalar loss and gradients, stabilizing training with small batches and reducing hyperparameter sensitivity typical of consumer GPUs. Throughout, only the prefixes, adapter banks, routers, and layer gates are trainable; the base model remains frozen.\n\nAt inference, the model loads just the selected‑layer prefixes, adapter banks, and tiny router. For multi‑task or continual setups, we maintain one prefix per task/domain and share the adapter banks; swapping prefixes selects the behavior with negligible overhead. The small, routed adapter design keeps memory and latency close to the frozen base while delivering accuracy comparable to full fine‑tuning on many instruction‑following and domain adaptation workloads.",
  "rationale": "Targeting late layers concentrates adaptation capacity where decoder backbones encode task‑specific behavior, allowing a tiny number of parameters to effect large changes. Cross‑layer global prefixes act like a task attribute that conditions attention everywhere it matters, while the local low‑rank adapters provide just‑enough capacity to reshape computations. Prototype‑routed mixtures increase expressivity under the same budget and supply an uncertainty signal we can exploit to allocate updates and prevent overfitting.\n\nUncertainty‑guided prompt updates and adversarial feature alignment preserve generalization and mitigate catastrophic forgetting when training with small batches on consumer hardware. Finally, a loss‑adaptive, momentum‑aware optimizer with online noise estimation stabilizes the small set of trainable parameters without expensive tuning. Together, these ingredients allow SGLA to approach or match full fine‑tuning performance for many tasks while adding orders‑of‑magnitude fewer parameters and fitting comfortably on commodity GPUs.",
